						<p>Price improvement details provided for domestic stock and single leg option orders entered during market hours after the primary opening, provided there is a National Best Bid and Offer (NBBO) at the time the order is placed. Price improvement details are provided for informational purposes only and are not used for regulatory reporting purposes.</p> 

						<p>Buy market orders with a weighted average <a href="javascript:popLargerWin('https://scs.fidelity.com/webxpress/help/topics/help_definition_e.shtml#executionprice')">execution price</a> below the National Best Offer (NBO) are considered price improved. Price improvement for buy market orders is calculated by subtracting the weighted average execution price from the NBO, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on buy limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the NBO minus the execution price and the limit price minus the execution price. Sell market orders with a weighted average execution price above the National Best Bid (NBB) are considered price improved. Price improvement for sell market orders is calculated by subtracting the NBB from the weighted average execution price, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on sell limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the execution price minus the NBB and the execution price minus the limit price.</p> 
						
						<p>Prior to December 7, 2015, price improvement for limit orders (buy and sell) was calculated using the methodology for price improvement on market orders described above.</p>
						
						<p>For buys and sells, price improvement is displayed per execution and per order, only when an order has been net price improved. Price improvements at the execution and individual order level are rounded down to the nearest penny.</p>

						<p>Price improvement details provided for domestic stock and single leg option orders entered during market hours after the primary opening, provided there is a National Best Bid and Offer (NBBO) at the time the order is placed. Price improvement details are provided for informational purposes only and are not used for regulatory reporting purposes.</p> 

						<p>Buy market orders with a weighted average <a href="javascript:popLargerWin('https://scs.fidelity.com/webxpress/help/topics/help_definition_e.shtml#executionprice')">execution price</a> below the National Best Offer (NBO) are considered price improved. Price improvement for buy market orders is calculated by subtracting the weighted average execution price from the NBO, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on buy limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the NBO minus the execution price and the limit price minus the execution price. Sell market orders with a weighted average execution price above the National Best Bid (NBB) are considered price improved. Price improvement for sell market orders is calculated by subtracting the NBB from the weighted average execution price, then multiplying by the number of executed shares to arrive at the net price improvement for the order. Price improvement on sell limit orders is calculated as the lesser of the execution price minus the NBB and the execution price minus the limit price. </p> 
						
						<p>Prior to December 7, 2015, price improvement for limit orders (buy and sell) was calculated using the methodology for price improvement on market orders described above.</p>
						
						<p>Some orders may not receive any price improvement. Fast market conditions and large order sizes relative to the bid or ask size may result in shares executing at or outside the NBBO. To learn more about our commitment to execution quality, click <a href="javascript:popLargerWin('https://www.fidelity.com/trading/execution-quality/overview')">here.</a></p>
						
						<p>Total Price Improvement reflects the sum of net price improvements on eligible orders executed within the stated timeframe. Orders with a weighted average execution price above the ask (for buys) or below the bid (for sells) are not factored into the Total Price Improvement figures. See <a href="javascript:popLargerWin('https://www.fidelity.com/trading/faqs-placing-orders')">Trading FAQs <img class="account-selector-close-control--icon" src="https://www.fid-inv.com/webcontent/ap110184-client-portfolio/73.1/images/dev/popup_blue.gif" height="12" width="12" style="vertical-align: top;" alt="Open Trading FAQ" /></a> for more information.</p>
						 
				</div>			
				
			<!-- End of Price Improvement Phase 4 -->	
			<!-- Start of todays markets disclosure -->  
                 <div id="legal-footer--todays-markets" class="legal-footer--item-content-detail show-in-print legal-footer--linkShow" style="display: none;">
                                 <p>Today's Markets provides access to quotes, delayed by 10 minutes, for select front-month futures contracts. The front-month contract will automatically roll to the next contract month upon expiration, when it has an open interest more than twice the current month, or its trading volume is larger.</p>
                 </div>
			<!-- End of todays markets disclosure  --> 
			
			<!-- Start of Retirement RPM disclosure -->  
                 <div id="legal-footer--rpm" class="legal-footer--item-content-detail show-in-print is-open" style="display: block;">
                                 <p><b>IMPORTANT: The projections or other information generated by the Planning & Guidance Center's Retirement Analysis regarding the likelihood of various investment outcomes are hypothetical in nature, do not reflect actual investment results, and are not guarantees of future results. Your results may vary with each use and over time.</b></p>
                 				 <p>Retirement Analysis, including the Retirement Preparedness Measure (RPM), is based on information you provided and certain assumptions, including market performance assumptions based on hypothetical scenarios using historical index data. Numerous factors make the calculations uncertain, such as the use of assumptions about historical returns and inflation, as well as the data you have provided. Fund fees and other expenses will generally reduce your actual investment returns and are generally not reflected in the hypothetical projections.</p>
                 </div>
			<!-- End of Retirement RPM disclosure disclosure  -->

You should use the official tax forms that Fidelity sends by mail for purposes of tax return preparation. Fidelity and National Financial Services (NFS) specifically disclaim any liability arising out of a customer's use of, or any tax position taken in reliance upon, such information.</p>
				<p>Unless otherwise specified, NFS determines cost basis at the time of sale based on the average cost method for open-end mutual funds and based on the first-in, first-out (FIFO) method for all other securities.</p>
				<p>A covered tax lot indicates that Fidelity will include cost basis and holding period information on the annual 1099-B for the year the tax lot is closed. Consult your tax advisor for further information.</p>
